We took a long time coming around to confidence in the safety of vaccines, and it had nothing to do with the Wakefield study.  I have read the VAERS database.  I read all of the inserts.  I have experienced the incredibly condescending attitudes and commentary of "scientifically-minded" people.  I have also watched a friend whose daughter contracted GBS after an early HPV shot.  I have a compromised immune system.  There was no certaintly when my child was an infant that he would not experience the same health issues I have.  We chose to be cautious.  We have started spacing out his vaccines over time to make sure we can monitor for any adverse reactions.  AND I DON'T CARE about other people's shaming tactics.  We are going to do what we feel is right for our family after speaking with our doctors.  Have vaccines contributed to an overall decline in childhood illnesses?  Yes.  I believe that.  But I also think that a one-sized fits all approach to medicine can be harmful.
